[{"sha":"90f57f3965ad1da050e5d3b81fb040ac78ca9a50","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix all-reduce related passes to delete dead all-reduce instructions
- Fix both all-reduce => reduce-scatter and all-reduce reassociation passes to delete
  existing all-reduce instructions that are dead after the pass.
- `RemoveInstructionAndUnusedOperands` may not remove all-reduce operands with
   channel_id, so we need to explicitly remove them.
- Also extended all-reduce reassociate to check use_count() == 1 to make sure that
   deleting the old all-reduce instructions after the transformation is ok.
- Extended test cases to verify that the existing all-reduce instructions are deleted post
  transformation.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[NFC] Remove completely-unused `*ConvolveBackwardBias` methods.

As far as I can tell from code archaeology, these have always been unused since
they were added in 2016, except in one solitary test that's long since been
deleted.

This operation is so trivial that there's really no point in calling into cuDNN
for it anyway: just sum over slices of the conv output's gradient tensor.  This
provides a possible reason why it's never been used: perhaps instead we just
used the gradient of the simple broadcast+add implementation of the bias.

Moreover, since cuDNN convolutions are generally moving towards the cuDNN
Backend API and away from per-operation C entry points, it's unlikely we'd end
up using this even if we did want to call into cuDNN for the functionality.

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LY-I/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"},{"sha":"d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove internal `act` builds from public modules (#21721)

Test for fix added in #21740","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LY-I/react/commits/e2453e2007083a67bf93f59c8ef2f39df2aaf636"},{"sha":"cae635054e17a6f107a39d328649137b83f25972","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act`: Resolve to return value of scope function (#21759)

When migrating some internal tests I found it annoying that I couldn't
return anything from the `act` scope. You would have to declare the
variable on the outside then assign to it. But this doesn't play well
with type systems — when you use the variable, you have to check
the type.

Before:

```js
let renderer;
act(() => {
  renderer = ReactTestRenderer.create(<App />);
})

// Type system can't tell that renderer is never undefined
renderer?.root.findByType(Component);
```

After:

```js
const renderer = await act(() => {
  return ReactTestRenderer.create(<App />);
})
renderer.root.findByType(Component);
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LY-I/react/commits/cae635054e17a6f107a39d328649137b83f25972"},{"sha":"d483463bc86555decb3e8caa18459d1d0f7c0148","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Updated scripts and config to replace "master" with "main" branch (#21768)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/LY-I/react/commits/d483463bc86555decb3e8caa18459d1d0f7c0148"},{"sha":"83f38d07689b8b750b7d96e17647a8978b836154","author":{"name":"dependabot[bot]","email":"1c358da00a777d4e9898c1280ab801e2df165188@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Bump ecstatic from 2.2.1 to 2.2.2 in /scripts/bench (#20468)

the `discreteUpdates` method used by our event system is only a
optimization to save us from having to check `window.event.type` on

[{"sha":"ef66da2e6189d11e58539948aee4f4841ee73cd0","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: MultiInstance interface to generalize count+for_each

We've developed a bunch of different places where we repeat the pattern
of asking for the references for the count and for_each expressions of
either a resource config or module call config object.

To cut down on that repetition (and thus potential for divergence), here
we add a new interface configs.MultiInstance which both Resource and
ModuleCall implement. We then use that interface as part of the
helper function lang.ReferencesForExpansion, which encapsulates the common
task of interrogating both of the expansion-related expressions to find
all of the dependencies that we need to deal with before we can "expand"
the graph node representing a resource or module call.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ef66da2e6189d11e58539948aee4f4841ee73cd0"},{"sha":"23a9b31764e70ee6604dda106b48f4b5b94e247c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"WIP validation of moves","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/23a9b31764e70ee6604dda106b48f4b5b94e247c"}]

[{"sha":"ea06130e24f52645438a488e6b5d8d5899d0428f","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[NFC] Remove completely-unused `*ConvolveBackwardBias` methods.

As far as I can tell from code archaeology, these have always been unused since
they were added in 2016, except in one solitary test that's long since been
deleted.

This operation is so trivial that there's really no point in calling into cuDNN
for it anyway: just sum over slices of the conv output's gradient tensor.  This
provides a possible reason why it's never been used: perhaps instead we just
used the gradient of the simple broadcast+add implementation of the bias.

Moreover, since cuDNN convolutions are generally moving towards the cuDNN
Backend API and away from per-operation C entry points, it's unlikely we'd end
up using this even if we did want to call into cuDNN for the functionality.

Previously, the recently-added "stable" Java targets excluded the
experimental _native_ APIs, but did NOT exclude the experimental _Java_ APIs,
with the result that use of experimental Java APIs would result in a run-time exception. With this change, attempts to use experimental Java APIs from code
that depends only on the "stable" Java targets will now result in compile-time
errors, since the stable targets only export classes/interfaces that don't have
any experimental methods (apart from one exception: `Tensor.asReadOnlyBuffer`).

This required adding a new `InterpreterFactory` class, to allow code using the
stable targets to allocate instances of `InterpreterApi` without depending on `Interpreter`. The `InterpreterFactory` class has a static `create` method that allocates an `Interpreter` instance, but returns a value of type `InterpreterApi`,
which is a restricted interface that only exposes the non-experimental
`Interpreter` methods.

The "stable" Java targets now don't expose `Interpreter` (or `Delegate`),
and instead expose `InterpreterFactory` and `InterpreterApi`.

Also add test `InterpreterApiTest` containing unit tests of `InterpreterFactory` / `InterpreterApi`.

Also update `InterpreterTest` to use try-with-resources rather than explicit close() calls.

[{"sha":"f6f0470893f69bed707935993e00dbdb21990c56","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Ensure "stable" targets don't expose experimental APIs, & add `InterpreterFactory`.

Previously, the recently-added "stable" Java targets excluded the
experimental _native_ APIs, but did NOT exclude the experimental _Java_ APIs,
with the result that use of experimental Java APIs would result in a run-time exception. With this change, attempts to use experimental Java APIs from code
that depends only on the "stable" Java targets will now result in compile-time
errors, since the stable targets only export classes/interfaces that don't have
any experimental methods (apart from one exception: `Tensor.asReadOnlyBuffer`).

This required adding a new `InterpreterFactory` class, to allow code using the
stable targets to allocate instances of `InterpreterApi` without depending on `Interpreter`. The `InterpreterFactory` class has a static `create` method that allocates an `Interpreter` instance, but returns a value of type `InterpreterApi`,
which is a restricted interface that only exposes the non-experimental
`Interpreter` methods.

The "stable" Java targets now don't expose `Interpreter` (or `Delegate`),
and instead expose `InterpreterFactory` and `InterpreterApi`.

Also add test `InterpreterApiTest` containing unit tests of `InterpreterFactory` / `InterpreterApi`.

Also update `InterpreterTest` to use try-with-resources rather than explicit close() calls.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[NFC] Remove completely-unused `*ConvolveBackwardBias` methods.

As far as I can tell from code archaeology, these have always been unused since
they were added in 2016, except in one solitary test that's long since been
deleted.

This operation is so trivial that there's really no point in calling into cuDNN
for it anyway: just sum over slices of the conv output's gradient tensor.  This
provides a possible reason why it's never been used: perhaps instead we just
used the gradient of the simple broadcast+add implementation of the bias.

Moreover, since cuDNN convolutions are generally moving towards the cuDNN
Backend API and away from per-operation C entry points, it's unlikely we'd end
up using this even if we did want to call into cuDNN for the functionality.

Change-Id: I90a8ed9ba482b0b86cf09adcc984d3b5c4b7c02d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jenselofsson/tensorflow/commits/6ecb39e10c4f2bfed5f82a33f8effa6d29a43aa8"},{"sha":"f028df0ba2c1b0b8cbb6e667ded3665153f8d127","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Make TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass less conservative

Now TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass can merge resource reads and assigns with
TPUExecute when there are non-interfering resource accesses between read/assigns
and TPUExecute. Interference is checked with resource alias analysis, and now
the pass is a `PerFunctionAggregateAnalysisConsumerPass`.
Previously, the pass was too conservative and considered any resource access as
potentially interfering so in many valid cases we couldn't merge.
Also added tests, made terminology more consistent, and added debug messages.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 379611333
Change-Id: Iad64a1968be321b2e66c92181b64acab80d2a4a4","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jenselofsson/tensorflow/commits/c45d90eaaa14352f71fa3371c34b6f9948dd91f6"},{"sha":"d0e01d7e235b9abb48137e11462448b6e9442ec0","author":{"name":"Yang Chen","email":"b1c859b0203793580f6fafdc9e88d8c10428cc59@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Read from local in-process workers if one exists.

Added `target_workers` param to `data_service_ops.from_dataset_id` and
`data_service_ops.distribute`. Users can specify "AUTO", "ANY", or
"LOCAL" (case insensitive). If "AUTO", tf.data service runtime decides
which workers to read from. If "ANY", TF workers read from any tf.data
service workers. If "LOCAL", TF workers will only read from local
in-processs tf.data service workers. "AUTO" works well for most cases,
while users can specify other targets. For example, "LOCAL" would help
avoid RPCs and data copy if every TF worker colocates with a tf.data
service worker. Currently, "AUTO" reads from any tf.data service
workers to preserve existing behavior. The default value is "AUTO".

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[NFC] Remove completely-unused `*ConvolveBackwardBias` methods.

As far as I can tell from code archaeology, these have always been unused since
they were added in 2016, except in one solitary test that's long since been
deleted.

This operation is so trivial that there's really no point in calling into cuDNN
for it anyway: just sum over slices of the conv output's gradient tensor.  This
provides a possible reason why it's never been used: perhaps instead we just
used the gradient of the simple broadcast+add implementation of the bias.

Moreover, since cuDNN convolutions are generally moving towards the cuDNN
Backend API and away from per-operation C entry points, it's unlikely we'd end
up using this even if we did want to call into cuDNN for the functionality.

Change-Id: Ief1034a768146cf2a7e3fb24911fffc622018c7f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/ea06130e24f52645438a488e6b5d8d5899d0428f"},{"sha":"90f57f3965ad1da050e5d3b81fb040ac78ca9a50","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix all-reduce related passes to delete dead all-reduce instructions

PiperOrigin-RevId: 382645766
Change-Id: Ifaa3bc2efa58243eeb2eb6054cb69aefb66a5c1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/d5764c9fef8c9cb075ebbaab24459210afc216d7"},{"sha":"f6f0470893f69bed707935993e00dbdb21990c56","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Ensure "stable" targets don't expose experimental APIs, & add `InterpreterFactory`.

Previously, the recently-added "stable" Java targets excluded the
experimental _native_ APIs, but did NOT exclude the experimental _Java_ APIs,
with the result that use of experimental Java APIs would result in a run-time exception. With this change, attempts to use experimental Java APIs from code
that depends only on the "stable" Java targets will now result in compile-time
errors, since the stable targets only export classes/interfaces that don't have
any experimental methods (apart from one exception: `Tensor.asReadOnlyBuffer`).

This required adding a new `InterpreterFactory` class, to allow code using the
stable targets to allocate instances of `InterpreterApi` without depending on `Interpreter`. The `InterpreterFactory` class has a static `create` method that allocates an `Interpreter` instance, but returns a value of type `InterpreterApi`,
which is a restricted interface that only exposes the non-experimental
`Interpreter` methods.

The "stable" Java targets now don't expose `Interpreter` (or `Delegate`),
and instead expose `InterpreterFactory` and `InterpreterApi`.

Also add test `InterpreterApiTest` containing unit tests of `InterpreterFactory` / `InterpreterApi`.

Also update `InterpreterTest` to use try-with-resources rather than explicit close() calls.

The Envoy Prometheus endpoint supports passing a filtering regex in
the query parameters to limit the set of metrics that are returned.
This feature lets a metrics scraper scrape different sets of metrics
at different intervals.

This updates #1755.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/61a356702f266c2330ed86f925606a559f6df0b3"},{"sha":"60a631de1a16f38764e4d72436774ce0e52df1fa","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) raise the regex program size limit (#2139)

Even though regex program sizes are deprecated, Envoy still enforces
the default limit of 100 in the layered runtime. Since users have no
reasonable way to predict the size of some arbitrary regex or know
how that affect performance, just max out the limit. We have to use
UINT32_MAX here, because the actual check truncates the value. We also
set a warning limit to an arbitrary size value in case anyone looks at
logs and wants to optimize their regexes.

This fixes #2103.

* feat(*) add reference documentation generator

Add tooling to generate CLI reference documentation to the path named
in "$DESTDIR". The goal is for the website to generate reference docs
on each new version.

Per discussion in kuma-website#447, generate the command documentation
locally (as a side-effect of `make check`).

Disable the timestamp on the generated docs, because if we allow cobra to
emit the timestamp , then the docs change every time we run `make check`,
which is undesirable.

This updates kumahq/kuma-website#447.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/ecf68d9f189b5d691ae6cacfcc1e150e438d2231"},{"sha":"b780f95ae0af868d146992fa3306e42e84dd3c9c","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@gmail.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) Clear snapshots from cache on disconnect (#2172)

Previously we were pushing an empty snapshot on the cache when a dp was disconnecting.
This was causing the dp to get an empty snapshot after a restart.
This would cause listeners to disappear for a short time and causing the traffic going through the dp to fail.
We now clear the snapshot from the dp to avoid this behaviour.

Fix #2176

* feat(*) add reference documentation generator

Add tooling to generate CLI reference documentation to the path named
in "$DESTDIR". The goal is for the website to generate reference docs
on each new version.

Per discussion in kuma-website#447, generate the command documentation
locally (as a side-effect of `make check`).

Disable the timestamp on the generated docs, because if we allow cobra to
emit the timestamp , then the docs change every time we run `make check`,
which is undesirable.

This updates kumahq/kuma-website#447.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/ecf68d9f189b5d691ae6cacfcc1e150e438d2231"},{"sha":"b780f95ae0af868d146992fa3306e42e84dd3c9c","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@gmail.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) Clear snapshots from cache on disconnect (#2172)

Previously we were pushing an empty snapshot on the cache when a dp was disconnecting.
This was causing the dp to get an empty snapshot after a restart.
This would cause listeners to disappear for a short time and causing the traffic going through the dp to fail.
We now clear the snapshot from the dp to avoid this behaviour.

Fix #2176

Signed-off-by: Nikolay Nikolaev <nikolay.nikolaev@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/3ee310d1e1b924483c0b0850e52f08c40290391b"},{"sha":"46e5b11baf73409d04d6f2e4d941821475a4c179","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"chore(*) remove Dataplane ProxyType accessor (#2215)

Remove the (*Dataplane) ProxyType(), which makes the concept of proxy
types confusing.

Since the introduction of ZoneIngress, there are two distinct proxy
types used by kuma-dp - Dataplane and ZoneIngress. Since these are
distict Go and Protobuf types, (*Dataplane) ProxyType() can't ever
return `IngressProxyType`, and by extension should never return
anything other than `DataplaneProxyType`.

To clarify the distinction, we use (*Dataplane) IsGateway(), which
indicates a Dataplane proxy type operating in gateway mode and matches
the existing IsIngress() API.

Signed-off-by: Nikolay Nikolaev <nikolay.nikolaev@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/3ee310d1e1b924483c0b0850e52f08c40290391b"},{"sha":"46e5b11baf73409d04d6f2e4d941821475a4c179","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"chore(*) remove Dataplane ProxyType accessor (#2215)

Remove the (*Dataplane) ProxyType(), which makes the concept of proxy
types confusing.

Since the introduction of ZoneIngress, there are two distinct proxy
types used by kuma-dp - Dataplane and ZoneIngress. Since these are
distict Go and Protobuf types, (*Dataplane) ProxyType() can't ever
return `IngressProxyType`, and by extension should never return
anything other than `DataplaneProxyType`.

To clarify the distinction, we use (*Dataplane) IsGateway(), which
indicates a Dataplane proxy type operating in gateway mode and matches
the existing IsIngress() API.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/46e5b11baf73409d04d6f2e4d941821475a4c179"},{"sha":"8b13853da2a445c725d98d18b52e1dc15262f4f5","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-dp) validate the DP proxy type (#2186)

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/ec83eee3dbf11f1453f5db61685533489dc24e77"},{"sha":"e2bd183084de3871bfa737df15bb5d5014d22577","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) supported versions fix (#2193)

As we were using caret ranges `^` instead of tilde ranges `~`
to catch the latest versions (1.1.0, 1.2.0) both of them could
catch the 1.2.0 version. Versions are delivered to our gui
as a hashmap, and when gui on the 1.2.0 version was asking our api
for the supported version of envoy it could receive the response
from range `^1.2.0` and then, everything was fine, and sometimes
it could receive a response from the `^1.1.0` range, and then
it was displaying warning.

It was happening because in the gui, we are iterating over
the hashmap with versions, and there is no consistency in
the order of keys (which is normal).

Also added tests to make sure there is always only one constraint
per version, to not allow similar situation to happen again.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/e2bd183084de3871bfa737df15bb5d5014d22577"},{"sha":"06236c6ca44b4ce97fa439f4c885bfb823bc66d0","author":{"name":"Tharun Rajendran","email":"f3d48fe62515f0377e74502509c8a10b9baa06eb@live.com"},"message":"docs(*) generate man pages for kuma components (#2101)

Signed-off-by: Nikolay Nikolaev <nikolay.nikolaev@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/3ee310d1e1b924483c0b0850e52f08c40290391b"},{"sha":"46e5b11baf73409d04d6f2e4d941821475a4c179","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"chore(*) remove Dataplane ProxyType accessor (#2215)

Remove the (*Dataplane) ProxyType(), which makes the concept of proxy
types confusing.

Since the introduction of ZoneIngress, there are two distinct proxy
types used by kuma-dp - Dataplane and ZoneIngress. Since these are
distict Go and Protobuf types, (*Dataplane) ProxyType() can't ever
return `IngressProxyType`, and by extension should never return
anything other than `DataplaneProxyType`.

To clarify the distinction, we use (*Dataplane) IsGateway(), which
indicates a Dataplane proxy type operating in gateway mode and matches
the existing IsIngress() API.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/ec83eee3dbf11f1453f5db61685533489dc24e77"},{"sha":"e2bd183084de3871bfa737df15bb5d5014d22577","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) supported versions fix (#2193)

As we were using caret ranges `^` instead of tilde ranges `~`
to catch the latest versions (1.1.0, 1.2.0) both of them could
catch the 1.2.0 version. Versions are delivered to our gui
as a hashmap, and when gui on the 1.2.0 version was asking our api
for the supported version of envoy it could receive the response
from range `^1.2.0` and then, everything was fine, and sometimes
it could receive a response from the `^1.1.0` range, and then
it was displaying warning.

It was happening because in the gui, we are iterating over
the hashmap with versions, and there is no consistency in
the order of keys (which is normal).

Also added tests to make sure there is always only one constraint
per version, to not allow similar situation to happen again.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[NFC] Remove completely-unused `*ConvolveBackwardBias` methods.

As far as I can tell from code archaeology, these have always been unused since
they were added in 2016, except in one solitary test that's long since been
deleted.

This operation is so trivial that there's really no point in calling into cuDNN
for it anyway: just sum over slices of the conv output's gradient tensor.  This
provides a possible reason why it's never been used: perhaps instead we just
used the gradient of the simple broadcast+add implementation of the bias.

Moreover, since cuDNN convolutions are generally moving towards the cuDNN
Backend API and away from per-operation C entry points, it's unlikely we'd end
up using this even if we did want to call into cuDNN for the functionality.

Change-Id: Ief1034a768146cf2a7e3fb24911fffc622018c7f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ishwor2048/tensorflow/commits/ea06130e24f52645438a488e6b5d8d5899d0428f"},{"sha":"90f57f3965ad1da050e5d3b81fb040ac78ca9a50","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix all-reduce related passes to delete dead all-reduce instructions

  existing all-reduce instructions that are dead after the pass.

- Extended test cases to verify that the existing all-reduce instructions are deleted post
  transformation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 382645766
Change-Id: Ifaa3bc2efa58243eeb2eb6054cb69aefb66a5c1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ishwor2048/tensorflow/commits/d5764c9fef8c9cb075ebbaab24459210afc216d7"},{"sha":"f6f0470893f69bed707935993e00dbdb21990c56","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Ensure "stable" targets don't expose experimental APIs, & add `InterpreterFactory`.

Previously, the recently-added "stable" Java targets excluded the
experimental _native_ APIs, but did NOT exclude the experimental _Java_ APIs,
with the result that use of experimental Java APIs would result in a run-time exception. With this change, attempts to use experimental Java APIs from code
that depends only on the "stable" Java targets will now result in compile-time
errors, since the stable targets only export classes/interfaces that don't have
any experimental methods (apart from one exception: `Tensor.asReadOnlyBuffer`).

This required adding a new `InterpreterFactory` class, to allow code using the
stable targets to allocate instances of `InterpreterApi` without depending on `Interpreter`. The `InterpreterFactory` class has a static `create` method that allocates an `Interpreter` instance, but returns a value of type `InterpreterApi`,
which is a restricted interface that only exposes the non-experimental
`Interpreter` methods.

The "stable" Java targets now don't expose `Interpreter` (or `Delegate`),
and instead expose `InterpreterFactory` and `InterpreterApi`.

Also add test `InterpreterApiTest` containing unit tests of `InterpreterFactory` / `InterpreterApi`.

Also update `InterpreterTest` to use try-with-resources rather than explicit close() calls.

* feat(*) add reference documentation generator

Add tooling to generate CLI reference documentation to the path named
in "$DESTDIR". The goal is for the website to generate reference docs
on each new version.

Per discussion in kuma-website#447, generate the command documentation
locally (as a side-effect of `make check`).

Disable the timestamp on the generated docs, because if we allow cobra to
emit the timestamp , then the docs change every time we run `make check`,
which is undesirable.

This updates kumahq/kuma-website#447.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/ecf68d9f189b5d691ae6cacfcc1e150e438d2231"},{"sha":"b780f95ae0af868d146992fa3306e42e84dd3c9c","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@gmail.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) Clear snapshots from cache on disconnect (#2172)

Previously we were pushing an empty snapshot on the cache when a dp was disconnecting.
This was causing the dp to get an empty snapshot after a restart.
This would cause listeners to disappear for a short time and causing the traffic going through the dp to fail.
We now clear the snapshot from the dp to avoid this behaviour.

Fix #2176

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/ec83eee3dbf11f1453f5db61685533489dc24e77"},{"sha":"e2bd183084de3871bfa737df15bb5d5014d22577","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) supported versions fix (#2193)

As we were using caret ranges `^` instead of tilde ranges `~`
to catch the latest versions (1.1.0, 1.2.0) both of them could
catch the 1.2.0 version. Versions are delivered to our gui
as a hashmap, and when gui on the 1.2.0 version was asking our api
for the supported version of envoy it could receive the response
from range `^1.2.0` and then, everything was fine, and sometimes
it could receive a response from the `^1.1.0` range, and then
it was displaying warning.

It was happening because in the gui, we are iterating over
the hashmap with versions, and there is no consistency in
the order of keys (which is normal).

Also added tests to make sure there is always only one constraint
per version, to not allow similar situation to happen again.

Signed-off-by: Nikolay Nikolaev <nikolay.nikolaev@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/3ee310d1e1b924483c0b0850e52f08c40290391b"},{"sha":"46e5b11baf73409d04d6f2e4d941821475a4c179","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"chore(*) remove Dataplane ProxyType accessor (#2215)

Remove the (*Dataplane) ProxyType(), which makes the concept of proxy
types confusing.

Since the introduction of ZoneIngress, there are two distinct proxy
types used by kuma-dp - Dataplane and ZoneIngress. Since these are
distict Go and Protobuf types, (*Dataplane) ProxyType() can't ever
return `IngressProxyType`, and by extension should never return
anything other than `DataplaneProxyType`.

To clarify the distinction, we use (*Dataplane) IsGateway(), which
indicates a Dataplane proxy type operating in gateway mode and matches
the existing IsIngress() API.

The Envoy Prometheus endpoint supports passing a filtering regex in
the query parameters to limit the set of metrics that are returned.
This feature lets a metrics scraper scrape different sets of metrics
at different intervals.

This updates #1755.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/61a356702f266c2330ed86f925606a559f6df0b3"},{"sha":"60a631de1a16f38764e4d72436774ce0e52df1fa","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) raise the regex program size limit (#2139)

Even though regex program sizes are deprecated, Envoy still enforces
the default limit of 100 in the layered runtime. Since users have no
reasonable way to predict the size of some arbitrary regex or know
how that affect performance, just max out the limit. We have to use
UINT32_MAX here, because the actual check truncates the value. We also
set a warning limit to an arbitrary size value in case anyone looks at
logs and wants to optimize their regexes.

This fixes #2103.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/ce422f618a3dd23d9afefc5643611bc2b896506c"},{"sha":"61a356702f266c2330ed86f925606a559f6df0b3","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-dp) pass query parameters through the metrics hijacker (#2124)

The Envoy Prometheus endpoint supports passing a filtering regex in
the query parameters to limit the set of metrics that are returned.
This feature lets a metrics scraper scrape different sets of metrics
at different intervals.

This updates #1755.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/61a356702f266c2330ed86f925606a559f6df0b3"},{"sha":"60a631de1a16f38764e4d72436774ce0e52df1fa","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) raise the regex program size limit (#2139)

Even though regex program sizes are deprecated, Envoy still enforces
the default limit of 100 in the layered runtime. Since users have no
reasonable way to predict the size of some arbitrary regex or know
how that affect performance, just max out the limit. We have to use
UINT32_MAX here, because the actual check truncates the value. We also
set a warning limit to an arbitrary size value in case anyone looks at
logs and wants to optimize their regexes.

This fixes #2103.

[{"sha":"60a631de1a16f38764e4d72436774ce0e52df1fa","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) raise the regex program size limit (#2139)

Even though regex program sizes are deprecated, Envoy still enforces
the default limit of 100 in the layered runtime. Since users have no
reasonable way to predict the size of some arbitrary regex or know
how that affect performance, just max out the limit. We have to use
UINT32_MAX here, because the actual check truncates the value. We also
set a warning limit to an arbitrary size value in case anyone looks at
logs and wants to optimize their regexes.

This fixes #2103.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[NFC] Remove completely-unused `*ConvolveBackwardBias` methods.

As far as I can tell from code archaeology, these have always been unused since
they were added in 2016, except in one solitary test that's long since been
deleted.

This operation is so trivial that there's really no point in calling into cuDNN
for it anyway: just sum over slices of the conv output's gradient tensor.  This
provides a possible reason why it's never been used: perhaps instead we just
used the gradient of the simple broadcast+add implementation of the bias.

Moreover, since cuDNN convolutions are generally moving towards the cuDNN
Backend API and away from per-operation C entry points, it's unlikely we'd end
up using this even if we did want to call into cuDNN for the functionality.

  existing all-reduce instructions that are dead after the pass.
- `RemoveInstructionAndUnusedOperands` may not remove all-reduce operands with

- Also extended all-reduce reassociate to check use_count() == 1 to make sure that

- Extended test cases to verify that the existing all-reduce instructions are deleted post
  transformation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 382645766
Change-Id: Ifaa3bc2efa58243eeb2eb6054cb69aefb66a5c1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/d5764c9fef8c9cb075ebbaab24459210afc216d7"},{"sha":"f6f0470893f69bed707935993e00dbdb21990c56","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Ensure "stable" targets don't expose experimental APIs, & add `InterpreterFactory`.

Previously, the recently-added "stable" Java targets excluded the
experimental _native_ APIs, but did NOT exclude the experimental _Java_ APIs,
with the result that use of experimental Java APIs would result in a run-time exception. With this change, attempts to use experimental Java APIs from code
that depends only on the "stable" Java targets will now result in compile-time
errors, since the stable targets only export classes/interfaces that don't have
any experimental methods (apart from one exception: `Tensor.asReadOnlyBuffer`).

This required adding a new `InterpreterFactory` class, to allow code using the
stable targets to allocate instances of `InterpreterApi` without depending on `Interpreter`. The `InterpreterFactory` class has a static `create` method that allocates an `Interpreter` instance, but returns a value of type `InterpreterApi`,
which is a restricted interface that only exposes the non-experimental
`Interpreter` methods.

The "stable" Java targets now don't expose `Interpreter` (or `Delegate`),
and instead expose `InterpreterFactory` and `InterpreterApi`.

Also add test `InterpreterApiTest` containing unit tests of `InterpreterFactory` / `InterpreterApi`.

Also update `InterpreterTest` to use try-with-resources rather than explicit close() calls.

Change-Id: I16e30311fded713c50107def5a4e8a0bf8609a1f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/a43e40d716f6ed64d3b2ebe3100b1d30ca67faf5"},{"sha":"a04cbff313889e1a1617f0b8615405365797fbf5","author":{"name":"Pulkit Bhuwalka","email":"1c7316b4758571ffd5669d96d1f7632f76c7fc28@google.com"},"message":"Fixing return from Status::OK() to statusHandler.ConsumeStatus()

The existing code returns Status::OK() which breaks if there are unhandled
errors. In those case, it causes the StatusHandler destructor to cause
a crash. It's better to return ConsumeStatus() so it handles the
errors properly.

* Warn if MutableSource snapshot is a function

useMutableSource does not properly support snapshots that are functions. In part this is because of how it is implemented internally (the function gets mistaken for a state updater function). To fix this we could just wrap another function around the returned snapshot, but this pattern seems problematic to begin with- because the function that gets returned might itself close over mutable values, which would defeat the purpose of using the hook in the first place.

This PR proposes adding a new DEV warning if the snapshot returned is a function. It does not change the behavior (meaning that a function could still work in some cases- but at least the current behavior prevents passing around a closure that may later become stale unless you're really intentional about it e.g. () => () => {...}).

Facebook currently relies on being able to hydrate hidden HTML. So
skipping those trees is a regression.

We don't have a proper solution for this in the new API yet. So I'm
reverting it to match the old behavior.

Now the server renderer will treat LegacyHidden the same as a fragment,
with no other special behavior. We can only get away with this because
we assume that every instance of LegacyHidden is accompanied by a host
component wrapper. In the hidden mode, the host component is given a
`hidden` attribute, which ensures that the initial HTML is not visible.
To support the use of LegacyHidden as a true fragment, without an extra
DOM node, we will have to hide the initial HTML in some other way.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/motiz88/react/commits/03e6b8ba2fb1c2820d2a5286701ff2b40590b438"},{"sha":"bb2239dc90015ced86177adc522de568198e2edc","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Revert "Feature: Add support to `exhaustive-deps` rule for any hook ending with `Effect` (#18580)" (#19004)

Tang","email":"765086fe2e0c1f980161f127fec596800f327f62@outlook.com"},"message":"Wire up set_filesystem_configuration with modular file system

This PR tries to wire up set_filesystem_configuration with
modular file system so that it is possible to set up the file
system configuration through modular file system plugins.

While set_filesystem_configuration API has been defined in
the past, the API was not wired up with modular file system
so it was not possible to use it from plugins.

This PR adds the missing implementation.

This PR also made several changes:
- values associated with `type_tag` was not defined in the past. This
  PR adds the definition.
- TF_Filesystem_Option_Value definition has been modified as previous
  unnamed union was difficult to assign value.
- set_filesystem_configuration_option was removed as it is almost
  a duplicate of set_filesystem_configuration, and it does not
  match the description.

While the API was modified, since set_filesystem_configuration
was not wired with modular file system, it is not used anyway.
So this will not break user or plugins.

[{"sha":"848ef3ece034c070bce9882c0a215ff579bd583b","author":{"name":"Maxiwell S. Garcia","email":"9e1524e90d3b98356dbf2c8ff6a781b1de473c4a@linux.ibm.com"},"message":"Disable ppc64le custom gemm_pack_rhs to use the convolution specialization

Eigen ppc64le has a gemm_pack_rhs specialization for AltiVec architecture.
TF Convolution also specializes this packing routine, improving the Tensor
code and avoiding a lot of index computation. Based on eigen_benchmark_cpu_test,
we found a good scenario for ppc64le, where gemm_pack_rhs from TF headers
together with VSX/MMA from ppc64le speeds up the performance of convolution.

This patch fixes the column computation for convolution in case of ppc64le
and disables the Eigen ppc64le gemm_pack_rhs using the define
EIGEN_ALTIVEC_USE_CUSTOM_PACK=0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/maxiwell/tensorflow/commits/848ef3ece034c070bce9882c0a215ff579bd583b"}]

Change-Id: Ifea0e7dccf1d29ef47e16e929148f08d4fe23f67","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jlrts/tensorflow/commits/8f4190c95f4609a78173676e7474d466d8ff6268"},{"sha":"30e65e8de17a2c32a7d70a67e35823224de8187e","author":{"name":"Jeremy Meredith","email":"e623f03c87c36e14fb66e36c2983621bef758449@google.com"},"message":"Adding tool to generate C++ experimental ops in-place (should be a no-op after formatting) along with an underlying framework for working with ops and code generation.

The script is located at:
tensorflow/c/experimental/ops/update_cpp_ops.sh

* Run this script when any of the generated C++ op definitions change in the registry.
* It pulls documentation from the API defs, e.g. the summary/description. The script should thus also be run when the API def changes; this will update the comments in the generated code.
* It currently contains the list of operators to generate and their categorizations; modify the script to add ops or change their target source file (e.g. array_ops vs math_ops).
* The script is configured to overwrite the existing ops in-place at: tensorflow/c/experimental/ops/*_ops.{cc,h}

Running this script should be a no-op, generating identical code for the C++ ops -- other than formatting (line wrapping specifically).

Currently when building TF with `--config=rocm`, we default to using C++11 (`-std=c++11` is explicitly added as a `cxx_flag` inthe crosstool wrapper).

Linux CPU builds (i.e. non-ROCm builds) already use C++14 as the default, and hipcc/hipclang will soon update the default to be C++14 as well.

This PR/commit updates the crosstool wrapper to add `-std=c++14` as the `cxx_flag` (instead of the current `-std=c++11`)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jlrts/tensorflow/commits/e8468b67cee2a71a7f53e6cba6f8f6aa5d0b35e9"},{"sha":"394a74b56a27006be6b0de289cbb80443c830590","author":{"name":"Dave Moore","email":"d1e2c048df802fa00ca98fd8ad6a2d561f813eb7@google.com"},"message":"Implement pfor convertors for PrintV2 (`tf.print`) and StringFormat ops.

Change-Id: I54838c5bbc5560180f844ee5baa9542e61ab25ba","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jlrts/tensorflow/commits/adf528c61e985fc66d84397f8f60f840fd8bc1c5"},{"sha":"b9d2c70915ec9997b0f45fa722166d9fbcc31f58","author":{"name":"Matt Watson","email":"1a665c2a0e9d672d25454bd51a7db62c9997cd45@google.com"},"message":"Add 'one_hot' output mode to CategoryEncoding, remove upranking in multi_hot

'one_hot' will automatically uprank the last dimension of your input if necessesary,
and create an encoding for every element in the batch individually. By adding this
explicit output_mode, we can remove the implicit behavior where output_mode='multi_hot'
would uprank all vector inputs and effectively one hot encode them. This allows
'multi_hot' and 'count' encoding unbatched multi-dimensional samples in a
tf.data.Dataset.

Signed-off-by: Bastien Chatelard <bastien@koyeb.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jpeach/kuma/commits/b3e04980ff768e8f4c7cc36b4d1c5ab3cba76fbc"},{"sha":"d2710d6166f4c42bb594708c50c1545190c2ba6c","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"chore(*) make the authentication interface type oblivious (#2271)

There are two proxy types that can be authenticated and in the future
there may be more. Rather than adding a new method for authenticating
each proxy type, switch to authenticating a generic model Resource and
allow each authenticator implentation to type switch internally.

This allows the xDS authentication callbacks to be insensitive to the
DP proxy type, except when fetching an existing resource, which needs
to allocate an instance of the concrete type.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jpeach/kuma/commits/d2710d6166f4c42bb594708c50c1545190c2ba6c"},{"sha":"82759d6459ba8584a701df2ba110cc830c110ba0","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"chore(*) generate DeepCopy interfaces

Enable DeepCopy interface generation for Kubernetes resources. This takes
advantage of the fact that if a type already implementes the DeepCopy
interface, deepcopy-gen will use it. This means that we can wrap the
raw protbuf message fields in a type that supports the interface and
then generate everything else.

This updates #2130.

[{"sha":"3268a7eabac90d3b06adeb3599734707be4b5148","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/output: Raw output mode

So far the output command has had a default output format intended for
human consumption and a JSON output format intended for machine
consumption.

However, until Terraform v0.14 the default output format for primitive
types happened to be _almost_ a raw string representation of the value,
and so users started using that as a more convenient way to access
primitive-typed output values from shell scripts, avoiding the need to
also use a tool like "jq" to decode the JSON.

Recognizing that primitive-typed output values are common and that
processing them with shell scripts is common, this commit introduces a new
-raw mode which is explicitly intended for that use-case, guaranteeing
that the result will always be the direct result of a string conversion
of the output value, or an error if no such conversion is possible.

Our policy elsewhere in Terraform is that we always use JSON for
machine-readable output. We adopted that policy because our other
machine-readable output has typically been complex data structures rather
than single primitive values. A special mode seems justified for output
values because it is common for root module output values to be just
strings, and so it's pragmatic to offer access to the raw value directly
rather than requiring a round-trip through JSON.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pdecat/terraform/commits/3268a7eabac90d3b06adeb3599734707be4b5148"},{"sha":"48d35b93329a720a87b77fa44e3f202761315c89","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"website: Fix a stray broken link to 0.8 -> 0.9 backend upgrade doc

* rename files for consistency with contents

* terraform: refactor EvalValidateSelfref

The EvalValidateSelfref eval node implementation was removed in favor of a regular function.

* terraform: refactor EvalValidateProvisioner

EvalValidateProvisioner is now a method on NodeValidatableResource.

* terraform: refactor EvalValidateResource

EvalValidateResource is now a method on NodeValidatableResource, and the
functions called by (the new) validateResource are now standalone
functions.

This particular refactor gets the prize for "most complicated test
refactoring".

* terraform: refactor EvalMaybeTainted

EvalMaybeTainted was a relatively simple operation which never returned
an error, so I've refactored it into a plain function and moved it into
the only file its called from.

* terraform: eval-related cleanup

De-exported preApplyHook, which got missed in my general cleanup sweeps.

Removed resourceHasUserVisibleApply in favor of moving the logic inline
- it was a single-line check so calling the function was (nearly) as
much code as just checking if the resource was managed.

* terraform: refactor EvalApplyProvisioners

EvalApplyProvisioners.Eval is now a method on

- For anytrue: any elements are unknown and no known elements are true
